author: {'steamid': '76561198446697083', 'num_games_owned': 887, 'num_reviews': 2, 'playtime_forever': 13170, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 9123, 'last_played': 1704417534}
review:
Antes que todo no se si todo el tiempo de juego que tengo se refleja en steam ya que lo juego de mediados del 2017, incluso lo hice diario por 2 a√±os aprox pero lo jugaba del celular, bajado de playstore. Actualmente lo juego de vez en cuando por nada en especial, en fin, no le crean a los frustrados que dicen que el juego es P2W, realmente si tiene sus compras dentro del juego, cosa que nunca he usado y aun asi el progreso del juego fue muy bueno, no entiendo a la gente que habla mal de los eventos, cartas nuevas, comunidad, etc. quiza no es un juego para ese tipo de personas, para que te guste un juego como este o cualquier YuGiOh te debe gustar el genero principalmente y tambien el modo que tiene especialmente este juego, que no solo es obtencion de cartas y ya, sino que tiene dinamicas diarias y semanales permanentemente. Sin necesidad de llegar al farmeo podes juntar muchos consumibles y cartas del juego, solo dedicandole algo de tiempo, repito, debe gustarte el genero. Y por ultimo, si nunca jugaste algun juego de cartas o mas en especifico de esta saga no te recomiendo empezar, actualmente por como avanz√≥ el juego es preferible licenciarte en alguna universidad o algo, es muy complicado aprender mecanicas, efectos, etc para la gente nueva, no es nada de otro mundo pero no creo que haya en nadie paciencia para hacerlo. 

Juego recomendadisimo para fans de la saga y si sos nuevo podes jugar con un amigo que ya sepa jugar, para que te tenga piedad porque en PvP nadie la tendr√° jaja

review:
I got back into Yu-Gi-Oh after rewatching the episode where Yugi won Slifer from "Strings". Playing this game is FUN.

Want new cards? Play against the computer or real people and get them from simple objectives.
Want Ultra Rare cards? Daily rewards and mission rewards have your back.
Want to play against or as your favourite character? Steady progression lets you!

The only drawback is the 3 zones in the monster and spell/trap fields and a few other restrictions, but this is a blast that is on "zoomies" for fans of the game, anime, and franchise!

author: {'steamid': '76561198073929645', 'num_games_owned': 100, 'num_reviews': 63, 'playtime_forever': 60800, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 434, 'last_played': 1704398391}
review:
The first online Yu-Gi-Oh game that I played. I played this game a lot in my phone and good thing that I can play it on my laptop too! I'll just warning you that this game can be addicted even if you would like to be as a F2P only, as there are countless of events and rewards that you can get within the game that can let you select cards that you want and gems to spend while trying to draw the card that you wanted within the game. 

Just an advice for new players 
- Try to search what is the current meta if you are a competitive person but be aware that those decks can be pretty expensive but still can be build by F2P by how much time you grind within the game and events. 
- There are plenty of F2P starter builds that doesn't require money or too much time on grinding as the deck I have been using was either the blue eyes deck and my favorite simple deck, "Red-Eyes Fusion Deck".
- Red-Eyes fusion deck is kinda a best F2P deck that I played since it can easily beat other players within just few rounds and you don't really need to spend so much time learning the spells and can be pretty annoy your opponents and of course also you (if you ever get matched against Red-Eyes fusion deck player)
- The good thing is that even if you have Red-Eyes fusion deck, you can still adjust some of the cards that you want to counter other decks like what I have done to my deck which makes the game pretty much interesting. 
- And finally, who doesn't want to collect those Exodia Deck, Egyptian Gods, and many cards from the original first Yu-Gi-Oh series.

L√≥gico que quando comecei n√£o tinham tantas cartas e arqu√©tipos como tem hoje em dia no game e por isso foi mais "tranquilo" de grindar, por√©m n√£o recomendo ningu√©m a iniciar no jogo hoje em dia a n√£o ser que esteja preparado pra gastar seu dinheiro em pacotes de cartas ao melhor estilo FIFA Ultimate Team.

Sin duda, un gran juego con doblaje en ingl√©s e idioma original en japon√©s.

author: {'steamid': '76561198167356491', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 10, 'playtime_forever': 29592, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 29525, 'last_played': 1707686825}
review:
It's not 100% real YuGiOh due to the 3 card monster and spell/trap limit as well as no Main Phase 2. If you're looking to learn real YuGiOh either download YGOPro or/and buy Legacy of the Duelist here on steam.

Here is a list of the differences from real TCG yugioh and Duel Links:
-Both players start with 4000LP
-Both players begin with 4 cards in their hand
-Main Phase 2 is completely absent from the game. In other words, after your battle phase is complete you must end your turn.
-There are only 3 monster and spell/trap card zones on the playing field.
-20card decks are the minimun.
-30card decks are the maximum.
-5 Monsters in extra deck is the maximum.
-No Synchro, XYZ, Pendelum OR Link summons.
-Characters will unlock a "skill" as they level which can be attached to a deck individually and activated in a duel when the conditions are met. For example, Yami Yugi has an ability called "Power of Dark" which allows him to play "Yami" at the very beginning of the duel for free right after the coin toss. The card is materialized from thin air and does not come from his deck.

With these differences some cards in this version of YGO are a lot more powerful due to the lower LP start and smaller decks. So you can definitely have some quick fun and pull off combos that you probably could hardly do in official YGO. Also, the voice acting is very nicely done.


For some people the differences between Duel Links and offical YGO may be a turn off. So I just want to make sure that you know the rules of this game and what you're getting into before you start investing in it.

author: {'steamid': '76561198257682341', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 19, 'playtime_forever': 749, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 749, 'last_played': 1683304964}
review:
Reminder che ho un telegram, √® molto bello e dovreste iscrivervi: https://t.me/nuskaclub

Quella che state per leggere non sar√† una recensione vera e propria come quelle che ho scritto di recente, la consider√≤ pi√π una raccolta di pensieri sparsi e soggettivi, in quanto non mi ritengo pienamente qualificato a parlare di Yugioh come gioco di carte.
Duel Links √® un approccio pi√π veloce e compatto del TGC, con un deck limitato a 20-30 carte, life points tagliati a met√† e 3 spazi per magie e mostri rispetto ai soliti 5.
Oltre a questo, esiste anche la presenza di personaggi selezionabili a rappresentarti in ogni duello, ognuno con un set di abilit√† che possono variare dall'aumento occasionale di certe statistiche, all'evocazione di magie terreno e molto altro.
Oltre che puntare le cose pi√π ovvie, come il ritmo dei duelli, non posso fare un paragone diretto col TGC perch√©, come ho detto, di quello che succede l√¨ so troppo poco per esprimermi, so solo che la mia esperienza online fin'ora √® stata tutto sommato molto divertente.
Questo √® il mio terzo tentativo di farmi piacere Duel Links, e fin'ora √® quello che si √® dimostrato pi√π fruttuoso, ma ci sono parecchie cose che non mi piacciono e su cui posso elaborare anche con la mia conoscenza limitata di ci√≤ che succede nella serie dopo i Synchro, molte delle quali incolpabili alla natura free-to-play dell'app pi√π che al formato di gioco.
Ero un gran fan della serie Tag Force da piccolo, quando non avevo nessuno con cui potevo giocare a Yugioh era il diversivo ideale. Realisticamente, dovrei aspettarmi lo stesso livello di qualit√† dal single player di Duel Links? Non credo sia giusto. Anche se fosse un gioco a prezzo pieno il suo punto forte √® ovviamente l'online, che in termini di contenuti e variet√† non mi d√† da lamentarmi.
Detto questo, √® una merda, e considerato quanto sia importante come fonte di grinding penso valga la pena spenderci su due parole.
Ogni "trama" √® suddivisa dalla serie di appartenenza, dentro al quale potrai usare tutti suoi i personaggi attinenti, per fare un esempio: in GX putrai usare Jaiden e non Yusei. Si comincer√† da Duel Monsters e col tempo sbloccherai tutte le altre serie.
Nulla di sbagliato con questo approccio, √® tutto il resto che non mi piace.
L'avrete probabilmente gi√† intuito, ma parola trama l'ho messa fra virgolette un paio di frasi perch√© descriverla come tale √® essere generosi. Riconosco che forse mi sto lamentando per qualcosa di cui dovrei aver chiss√† che aspettative, ma a me gli anime di Yugioh piacciono e i Tag Force avevano giusto un pochino di mordente in pi√π, se vogliamo parlare strettamente di videogiochi, √® cos√¨ tanto chiedere una storia decente? Boh.
Un'altro problema √® quanto sballata sia la difficolt√† dei duelli in generale. Mentre tu sei online a sperimentare con Pendulum e Xys gi√† dalle prime ore di gioco i tuoi avversari in single player useranno mostri vanilla con meno di 1000 punti d'attacco per una porzione ridicola di trama.
Questo grinding √® parzialmente alleggerito dalla presenza di auto-duelli che puoi tenere in background, ma anche appesantito dal respawn di duellanti molto lento.
Anche l'online non √® esente da difetti, per√≤, e dopo essermi abituato cos√¨ bene con Pok√©mon Showdown devo dire che la mancanza di una separazione netta fra i formati delle varie saghe mi ha lasciato un po' deluso. Mi ricordo ancora i primissimi tempi di Duel Links, quando ancora dovevano introdurre i Synchro e il metagame era completamente diverso da quello di adesso, e ritengo un spreco che quei giorni non possano pi√π tornare. Alla fine stiamo parlando di Yugioh, non credo che la fanbase sia cos√¨ piccola da creare problemi se si tengono assieme pi√π di un formato allo stesso tempo, no? Magari √® una richiesta irragionevole, ma leggere di come certe carte vecchie e ritenute inutili di 20 anni fa abbiano trovato una nicchia rilevante in Duel Links durante vari punti nella storia competitiva dell'app mi fa venir voglia di poterci sperimentare io stesso, e so che non posso perch√© non sarebbe pi√π fattibile nel meta corrente. Intanto, per√≤, se guardo in Showdown ci sono ancora sviluppi per il meta della terza generazione, cosa permessa dal fatto che esiste una separazione netta fra essa e ci√≤ che viene prima o dopo.
Mah.
Poi vab√®, le solite lamentele da gacha, che per√≤ devo dire si applicano anche al gioco di carte originale quindi non √® che posso dire pi√π di tanto.

review: I enjoyed playing Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links. It's simple and interesting to play because it's a miniature version of Yu-Gi-Oh. Certain cards are limited or restricted to ensure that everyone has an enjoyable experience. There are many characters to play and many cards to obtain. You can level up characters to earn rewards such as card, gems, coins, etc. In addition, there are many available game modes including dueling quizzes, PvC, PvP, casual duels, turbo duels, legacy duels, etc. All the different types of Special Summons are supported including Fusion, Synchro, XYZ, and Link Summoning. However, as more is added to the game, it negatively affects the gameplay experience. The majority of duels are being decided in the first few turns. Spells or Traps that can be activated when a monster declares a attack are less effective because most players are smart enough to destroy them. Players rely on cheap antics to get ahead. Regardless, it's a great game.

Le jeu est factuellement bon mais les mises √† jour r√©guli√®re emp√™che parfois les banlist ou la m√©ta de boug√© au bon moment mais cela √† aussi ces avantages parfois.
Le probl√®me r√©side dans l'√©conomie m√™me du jeu qui fait que si vous √™tes un nouveau joueur ou que si vous avez fait une pause vous ne pourrez pas rattrap√© votre retard vis √† vis dans la collection ce qui dans les fait vous bloquera d√®s que vous voudrez vous amusez en pve ou m√™me test√© des arch√©types.
Si jamais vous √™tes fan des anim√©s vous aurez des comp√©tences appropri√©s pour favoriser les arch√©types de ceux ci, ce qui est vraiment agr√©able.
Les √©v√©nements PvE sont int√©ressant m√™me si certain dur vraiment longtemps (genre 2,5 semaine alors que la plupart des √©v√©nements dure 10 jour). Je salut les √©v√©nement pvp pour leur innovation et pour r√©partir en niveau pas comme en class√©.
Les class√©s bien que j'ai un peux de mal avec ce concept que l'on retrouve dans absolument tous les jeux en ligne sont comme d'habitude le seul mod pvp pris en compte par le jeu.
Enfin bref je n'aime pas le pvp dans yugioh de un √† cause des timer(beaucoup trop court et surtout stressant pour rien) et de deux √† cause des m√©tas. Le pve √©tant le moteur du jeu mais sans plus (dommage ou tant mieux c'est l'avis de chacun)
Le rush duel, qui est un autre format du jeux, est pour le moment beaucoup trop jeune et les decks qui fonctionnent ne sont pas forc√©ment les mieux penser n√©anmoins je fonde de (trop grand) espoir sur ce mode.

review: For every Yu-Gi-Oh fan, from the most hardcore to the casual. I'd say its USP among all the other Yu-Gi-Oh video games is you get to hear the voice actors reprising their roles, including big legends like Eric Stuart, Wayne Grayson, Bella Hudson and of course Dan 'The Man' Green! The variety of skills available to each playable/unlockable character means there is plenty of mix-ups you can make which prevents the single player (at least) from going stale.

review: Its very addictive if you like the show and card game! Uses original voice actors and characters for every series from the first to v-rains.  Only 4000 life points like the show so it will be quick duels most of the time. Also adds character abilities to play key cards from the deck. Updates a lot for the forbidden/restricted list to keep the meta fresh and fair. It can be free to play if you attack it using your newbie rewards and grinding tools to form one deck so you can climb ranked. if you wanna have more fun with it you gotta be willing to spend on their deals for packs which can add up to high amounts of $. The game is good overall.

author: {'steamid': '76561198247167278', 'num_games_owned': 166, 'num_reviews': 6, 'playtime_forever': 60307, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 77, 'playtime_at_review': 59342, 'last_played': 1712448570}
review:
Title: "Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links: A Gacha Roller Coaster of Unfairness"

Rating: ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÜ‚òÜ‚òÜ

Oh, Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links, you tantalizing digital card game with your flashy animations and nostalgic duels. However, beneath the surface lies a gacha-infested world where fairness takes a back seat and frustration becomes your closest companion. This review aims to shed light on the game's unbalanced nature, leaving players at the mercy of unpredictable luck and pay-to-win mechanics.

Let's address the elephant in the room: the gacha system. Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links relies heavily on randomized card packs, promising rare and powerful cards that can turn the tide of any duel. But here's the catch‚Äîthese packs are often designed to drain your virtual wallet faster than you can say "Exodia, obliterate!" The game's obsession with microtransactions and the constant urge to spend real money to get an edge over opponents can quickly turn the experience into a frustrating and expensive endeavor.

Moreover, the rarity of certain cards creates a gaping chasm between players. Those lucky enough to pull rare and coveted cards have a significant advantage, while others are left struggling with lackluster decks. This imbalance tilts the playing field and turns duels into predictable outcomes, where luck matters more than skill. It's disheartening to invest time and effort into building a strategic deck, only to be consistently outmatched by players who simply lucked out on their gacha pulls.

The game's progression system is equally flawed. Duel Links heavily restricts access to certain cards and deck archetypes behind an artificial progression wall. This means that players who are unwilling or unable to spend copious amounts of time or money are left with limited options, stifling their creativity and strategic choices. It's disheartening to see the potential for diverse and unique decks, only to realize that they're locked away behind an unfair progression system.

Additionally, the reliance on pay-to-win mechanics takes away from the true essence of the Yu-Gi-Oh! experience. The game should be about strategic thinking, deck building, and outsmarting opponents. However, it becomes a mere race to acquire the rarest cards and overpower your opponents through brute force rather than skillful play. This shift in focus undermines the competitive nature of the game and leaves a bitter taste for players seeking a fair and balanced dueling experience.

In conclusion, Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links may offer a visually appealing trip down memory lane with its beloved characters and iconic duels. However, the game's heavy reliance on gacha mechanics, unfair progression systems, and pay-to-win elements tarnish the experience. It transforms what should be a strategic and skill-based card game into an unbalanced, frustrating, and financially draining endeavor. Proceed with caution, duelists, as the path to dueling greatness in Duel Links is paved with unfairness and disappointment.

author: {'steamid': '76561198068527419', 'num_games_owned': 172, 'num_reviews': 94, 'playtime_forever': 2904, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 2904, 'last_played': 1683733736}
review:
Yu-Gi-Oh is better than pokemon or any other cartoon there is.
About this game. Has a lot of cards to chose from. It's free. User friendly, excluding those pop ups and random events that may not be easy to skip, and you'd need to sit through them for 10 minutes. Game gives you lots of opportunities to get new cards for your collection and is overall user-friendly. The only downside for me would be that there is not enough cards for me. I'd love for it to have more of them. 

Regarding PvP. People use only one deck mainly, whatever may be in the meta / new cards added to the game. Everyone plays the same deck, there is just no variety. I myself have beloved the Toon Deck, and mixed it with red-dragon(s) cards, where i have seen only 3 people out of thousands that i've played, use Toon decks...

I all of my 1800 PvP fights, i have encountered 9 decks. 
Nine -- Decks in 1,800 Fights.
Everyone plays the same thing. Same tactics. Most of the people either leave for 170 seconds during the match forcing you to surrender not to waste your life on an AFK Opponent; where they'd come back after those 170 seconds to play, and rush their rounds to get some Time back (round limit is 180 seconds), or they would just move so slowly, that you could take a nap while the guy is thinking whether to set a card A or a card B...

author: {'steamid': '76561198976571265', 'num_games_owned': 18, 'num_reviews': 2, 'playtime_forever': 85, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 85, 'last_played': 1686021253}
review:
Insert you and friend playing this game*

So you're playing as Kaiba and they're playing as Yugi. 
You've drawn blue eyes, a defense block, attack block, and samurai card which you decide to play.
You realize you could use Blue eyes but the opportunity won't arrive for some time. 
Your opponent (Yugi Goodman) finds themselves in a bit of a bind. 
You draw another card which allows you to build up your field rather well, they however lack the cards and attack power to defend.
You draw one more card in this instance to have 3 cards in attack, two face down available at any time.
They ask for mercy around this time and you accept to let things build up in intensity (You have blue eyes ready.)
They have lemon magician on the field and a continuous spell which enables an effect. 
They are able to summon one more card due to this effect, it's another magician. 
You set this magician in defense using one of your face-down cards, you kill this magician. 
They draw a card, it has around 1900 atk thus overpowering your wall of monsters. Consequentially leaving you with only two. 
You ask for mercy and they say "It's only fair."
With your two remaining cards, tribute summon blue eyes.
Blue eyes in this moment would destroy everyone and win the game.

You (foolishly and stupidly) don't attack with blue eyes the moment you're able to.
You draw one card next to blue eyes, it's an armored dragon thing. 3-4 stars, low in comparison to blue eyes.
Afterwards they reveal that they've gotten a fusion summon card but is unaware on how to use it. 
They (Use it on whim). 

Note: They are Yugi and have built their entire deck around Dark magician. 

Their fusion summon brings Dark Magicians (Dark Magician and Dark magican girl.) Not enough to defeat blue eyes, but at this point in the battle it could kill my armored dragon.
My turn: I draw and end it hoping to extend the battle further, expecting them to reciprocate this as it's been. 
Note: This is just an assumption, I didn't openly state this. (My LP is moderately low right now due to my attack failing earlier and the effect of their earlier card.)

It's their turn, I have blue eyes and the armored dragon. 
They kill me with magicians by attacking the dragon.
I just stare at the screen while kaiba screams in agony.
Blue eyes stares back at me.
I realize my mistake and swear revenge. 
They believed in the heart of the cards. 
I believed in mutually assured destruction. (Blue eyes would've solo'd, nothing was mutual. Just a skill issue tbh.) 

Moral of the story, great game if you play it long enough. 7/10. Easy to understand and play. If you get blue eyes, just use it right off the bat. You've got nothing to lose except the damn game. F the heart of the cards.

review: I am a 45 yo father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 14 now. My son got this game for Christmas in 2021 from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game, picked my character and world and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he hosted a game for me to join. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my Son many happy memories.

review:
Giochino cacha pay to win, totalmente brainless ed ogni partita in rank √® scriptata. 

Puoi crearti il deck che vuoi, seguire le tierlist nelle community online, ma √® solo la combinazione di molta fortuna e molti soldi spesi a farti arrivare in alto. 
Non c'√® una reale bravura o competizione, tutto si basa su skills dei personaggi sbloccabili e carte comprate attraverso soldi reali... visto che su diversi box dove sono sbustabili 100 carte in totale, solo alcune possono essere sbustate con le gemme. 
Per farti un giro completo di sbustamenti di alcune box, sei obbligato a comprare e spendere soldi reali (e neanche pochi). 

Ti prende per i colori e gli effetti grafici che ti sparaflashano sullo schermo i premi, come se stessi giocando alle slot machine (poco ci manca a non renderlo tale) e per i nostalgici della serie... ma i veri giochi sono ormai sepolti da decenni nella tomba insieme alle vecchie console dove veramente ti divertivi e non c'erano script che decidevano il tuo destino nella rank.

review: Pretty good if you want to get into yugioh without as much of the card pool and a bit more simplicity to the game. Skills allow for decks which never saw competitive use in the TCG to be usable if not high tier, which is a lot of fun to see. Gameplay itself is a bit monotonous, especially if you are wanting to grind out all the achievements, but some of it is remedied by the auto-duel feature. Gem economy is pretty trash, but that's nothing new for this genre of game, so unless you are willing to drop lots of money to play certain decks, I would recommend looking online for decks that are competitive but also not to expensive. I have managed to build several competitive decks and have spent less than $10 total on this game.

Allora, iniziamo dicendo che questo gioco l'ho iniziato a giocare grazie a una cara amica, e dopo 400 ore di gioco direi che sono pi√π che in grado di esprimere il mio parere a riguardo. Iniziamo subito cos√¨ finiamo va.


La trama:

Abbastanza ignorante e simpatica da piacermi, in breve esiste un mondo virtuale chiamato Duel World dove i duellanti di tutti gli archi narrativi possono ritrovarsi e duellare. Semplice, carino e no sense come tutto il franchise, quindi passabile.


Il Gameplay:

Vi son piaciute le 3 righe di commenti positivi sopra? Bene, perch√© sono le uniche che leggerete in tutta la fottuta recensione. Se siete fan sfegatati di sto gioco preparatevi, perch√© sto per smontare pezzo per pezzo questo schifo di gioco. Partiamo dalla costruzione deck: o avete tante gemme da spendere o vi attaccate e tirate forte, PUNTO. Aggiungiamo anche il fatto che nelle box dove si trovano le carte le Ultra Rare queste ultime saranno limitate a 1 FOTTUTA COPIA PER BOX e vi cadranno le palle solo dopo aver capito quale sar√† la probabilit√† per ottenerle. Ah gi√†, ci sono i coupon da sogno, che te le fanno ottenere subito, ma te ne danno 1 SOLO PER RARITA' una volta ogni cambio di shampoo di Brad Pitt. Dimenticavo, SCORDATEVI di giocare for fun, su Duel Links credo ci sia la tana della feccia della community di Yu-Gi-Oh: tutti giocatori frustrati che prendendo calci in culo nella vita vera e piangendo come dei bambini di 5 anni si rintanano in sto aborto di gioco per sfogarsi sui pi√π deboli utilizzando i loro mazzi shoppati, e sto parlando sul serio: ho fatto un periodo giocando un mazzo old Chazz, con carte tipo Soldato Chthoniano, Polimerizzatore Chthoniano, X Testa Cannone... neanche il tempo di evocare normalmente Zombie Rinato, carta totalmente innocua sia di statistiche che di effetti, che sti beb√® attivano Libro Della Luna o Buco Trappola Chiuso per mettermelo coperto. Solo con amici si riesce a giocare for fun, unico motivo per il quale sto tenendo il gioco, e giocando da PC c'√® una connessione che non fa schifo, PEGGIO. 4 volte su 6 che inizio un duello o faccio una qualsiasi azione parte il solito messaggio "nEssuN4 c0nn3SS10n3 di r3t3!1!!1", quando ho tacche PIENE di connessione. Ma vi pesa il culo curare un po' di pi√π il vostro gioco Konami? Bilanciarlo magari con qualche banlist che impedisca a mazzi come il Solfaccordo e il Fiore Cardian di OTKappare? Nono √® vero, meglio mettere le poche carte che li contrastano a ULTRA e spargerle in pacchetti diversi. Poi se shoppi e sei un senzavita che non conosce cosa significhi mescolare un mazzo nella vita vera va bene, capisco che ritieni schifezze come questo gioco come "belle", ma se siete dei giocatori che voglion divertirsi facendo una partita a Yu-Gi-Oh! andate alla fumetteria pi√π vicina e duellate dal vivo, ci si diverte di pi√π e soprattutto non si hanno mani megascriptate per farti perdere (seriamente, avere tutti e 3 i diapason fiamma nel mazzo in mano con richiamo diapason e pescare sempre altri diapason √® ridicolo, non venitemi a dire che √® costruito male il mazzo perch√© √® un tentativo patetico di proteggere un gioco schifoso a spada tratta). Ultima nota, dolente ovviamente, √® il discorso Abilit√†: non per come funzionano, alla fine √® il modo che ha il gioco per rendersi unico, ma per il loro bilanciamento. Paragonando due personaggi come Crowler e Yubel sar√† pi√π facile capire: Crowler ha un massimo di Abilit√† che consente di evocare SENZA TRIBUTI Golem Ingranaggio Antico E immediatamente dopo posizionare una Polimerizzazione presa AL DI FUORI del deck. In breve potete evocare il Golem Megatonico al primo turno, in alternativa avrete un mostro che ha 3000 punti e che attaccando impedisce l'attivazione delle carte coperte, con danno perforante. Con Yubel invece? Semplicemente mescolate una delle forme di Yubel dalla mano nel vostro mazzo per tirare fuori quella originale sempre dal vostro mazzo. Fate voi i conti, anche se c'√® ben poco da capire.



Voto: 3/10, abbassato a un 1/10 per la strafottenza di Konami nell'ignorare questi problemi aggiornando costantemente il gioco

review:
Si os explico como he acabado jugando a este juego no os lo vais a creer , 
Un chatarrero de mi barrio encontr√≥ un mazo de cartas f√≠sicas unas 300, como no sab√≠a mucho sobre ellas , me dijo si pod√≠a buscar cuanto val√≠an... resulta que muchas eran falsas (sin holograma) y otras verdaderas ,  una de ellas val√≠a como 400 euros .

Antes de eso no conoc√≠a estos juegos de cartas y eso que joven no soy, pues  por culpa de mi colega me he metido de lleno en esto y es una pasada , no sab√≠a ni que hab√≠a un aplicaci√≥n en Steam para poder jugarlo.

A mi esto me parece increible y me  estoy viciado a esto de las cartas yugioh y pienso comprar algunas cartas de verdad para jugar en familia  (Mucho mejor que ver la televisi√≥n)

Si eres nuevo en esto te recomiendo que no te instales este juego , es pura droga "pal' celebro"  , no la instales , te estoy diciendo que pases de largo y no la instales....

Mira que te lo he avisado...... 

Pues nada  ahora te vas  a viciar como un perro .... la pr√≥xima vez haz caso de las rese√±as de los dem√°s.

Abrir sobrecitos es la aut√©ntica salud , sobre todo cuando te sale esa carta ultrarara. 

Los seres humanos somos adictos al azar , nos encanta eso de que nos pueda tocar un premio no tenemos remedio...

Si puedes comprate las cartas de verdad y sal a juega con tus amigos en la playa o en la piscina o en una terraza que es mas sano que estar pegado a un ordenador en un habitaci√≥n oscura.

author: {'steamid': '76561198059551616', 'num_games_owned': 360, 'num_reviews': 132, 'playtime_forever': 25094, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 823, 'playtime_at_review': 9332, 'last_played': 1712272223}
review:
"Duel Links" es un juego de cartas que combina diferentes series de la franquicia [i]Yu-Gi-Oh![/i] en un formato r√°pido con todos los tipos de invocaciones conocidos hasta la fecha.

El tablero consta de 3 espacios para cartas m√°gicas/de trampa/p√©ndulo, 3 para monstruos (m√°s 2 para invocaciones realizadas por fusi√≥n, sincron√≠a o enlace) y 1 para hechizos de campo. Esto va acompa√±ado del mazo que puede ser de 20 a 30 cartas con uno extra de 8 como m√°ximo.

Lo m√°s interesante son las habilidades de cada protagonista. Estas pueden alterar o ignorar reglas, como si fuera un duelo del anime donde cada personaje hace lo que quiere.

Se puede armar una gran variedad de mazos con las recompensas de los eventos y las monedas diarias pero si quieren jugar a nivel competitivo van a tener que invertir.

review:
Como un fan√°tico que no es tan fan√°tico de Yu-Gi-Oh desde hace alg√∫n tiempo, no pude resistirme a probar Yu-Gi-Oh Duel Links, y debo decir que, en su mayor parte, ¬°no me ha decepcionado! La experiencia de sumergirse en el mundo de Yu-Gi-Oh a trav√©s de este juego es simplemente genial, especialmente con la nostalgia que trae consigo.

La jugabilidad es s√≥lida y casi fiel al juego de cartas original, con una gran variedad de cartas y estrategias para explorar. Los duelos son emocionantes y bien equilibrados en su mayor parte, lo que ofrece una experiencia competitiva gratificante.

Sin embargo, debo se√±alar que el juego puede inclinarse hacia el lado del "P2W" (pagar para ganar) en ocasiones. Como jugador completamente F2P (Free to Play), not√© que a veces me encontraba en desventaja frente a aquellos que estaban dispuestos a invertir dinero en el juego. Esto puede resultar frustrante en ocasiones, especialmente cuando te enfrentas a oponentes con decks muy poderosos que parecen inalcanzables para los jugadores que no pagan.

A pesar de este inconveniente y de que puedes tal vez llegar a tener un deck como el que ellos tienen si te empe√±as en pasar mucho tiempo jugando y recolectando gemas (Lo cual tambi√©n es un poco dific√≠l), a√∫n as√≠ puedo decir que disfrut√© mucho de Yu-Gi-Oh Duel Links. La experiencia de juego en general es divertida y adictiva, especialmente para los jugadores de Yu-Gi-Oh como yo. Si puedes pasar por alto el aspecto ocasional de P2W y simplemente disfrutar del juego por lo que es, definitivamente vale la pena probarlo.

review:
Pretty fun and noob friendly, if you played as a kid, only watched the original show oreven if you are new to the franchise, the game have plenty tutorials and ways to get cards, you can get anything for free if you play enough (not even that much) and the updates and events help to keep the game alive.
Thanks to the character's abilities mostly of the old archetypes are at least playable and even competitive, and the speed duels makes it dynamic to play and test without being time consuming.
Pretty much everything in the game is good and a really nice experience (even better if you start to play with a friend to test yourselves meanwhile you progress).
Everything's good, except pendulum monsters, f*uck those guys.

review:
Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links is an incredibly fun and addicting game that will have you hooked for hours on end. Whether you're a longtime fan of the Yu-Gi-Oh! franchise or new to the game, Duel Links offers an engaging and accessible experience that is both challenging and rewarding.

One of the standout features of Duel Links is the game's intuitive and streamlined gameplay mechanics. The game's rules are easy to learn, yet there's still a surprising amount of depth to the strategy and tactics involved in winning duels. The game also features a wide variety of cards, each with its own unique effects and abilities, allowing you to customize your deck to your liking.

Another great aspect of Duel Links is the game's stunning visuals and sound design. The card designs are gorgeous and faithfully capture the essence of the Yu-Gi-Oh! franchise, while the music and sound effects add to the immersive experience of the game.

In addition, the game offers a wealth of content to keep you engaged for hours on end. The single-player campaign features a variety of challenges and missions, while the multiplayer mode allows you to compete against other players from around the world.

Overall, Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links is a fantastic game that is both fun and challenging. With its intuitive gameplay mechanics, stunning visuals, and wealth of content, it's a must-play for fans of the Yu-Gi-Oh! franchise and anyone looking for a fun and addicting card game.

author: {'steamid': '76561199092511494', 'num_games_owned': 3, 'num_reviews': 2, 'playtime_forever': 3566, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 3118, 'last_played': 1693654895}
review:
The card art, gameplay, and just about everything else about this game will bring back memories if you're a fan of the series. It is one of the top strategy games I've ever played. Even  if you've never watched the anime, you still get to see new cards and how they function

But the game's remarkable variety is what really caught my attention. There are a tonne of cards to collect and experiment with, from old favourites to brand-new additions that give the game a completely new level of strategy. Speaking about strategy, the gameplay is very entertaining; while it is simple to pick up, mastering it is an entirely different challenge.

Additionally, the game often releases updates and hosts events to keep things interesting, so there's always something to look forward to.

Overall, if you love card games in general or are a fan of the franchise, I'd say Yu-Gi-Oh Duel Links is certainly worth your time, considering I have 50+ hours on it, and nothing can compare to the joy of creating a powerful deck and winning games.

author: {'steamid': '76561198846538510', 'num_games_owned': 35, 'num_reviews': 10, 'playtime_forever': 24, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 24, 'last_played': 1531058612}
review:
I am a 45 years old father with a teenage son who loves playing video games. I have always struggled to connect with my son as he spends most of his free time playing games online or watching others play on YouTube. As a busy single father, I found it difficult to spend quality time with him.

But recently, my son introduced me to a game called Yu-Gi-Oh Duel Links, and I decided to create a Steam account so we could play together. It had been decades since I last played a video game, so I was quite rusty. But my son patiently taught me how to play and we started bonding over this game.

I was pleasantly surprised by how much fun we had playing together. It was like we were solving a mystery together, laughing and having a great time. Playing video games with my son reminded me of the joy of being a kid and it helped me to connect with my son on a whole new level. We even started spending more time together outside of the game, going on walks and enjoying other activities.

As a single father, it can be difficult to find common ground with my son, but video games have given us a new way to bond and spend quality time together. I am grateful for this opportunity to connect with my son and make lasting memories together.

review: Listen, if you grew up with Yu-GI-Oh duel monsters on TV then you will totally love this game. I've been playing the TCG for several years and this game is a duelist dream. This game allows you to build your favorite decks from characters you love or just build a deck you always wanted to run. Personally I love the graphics, cards details, reliving the lore from the anime/manga and card events. Can't lie that it does get difficult with people running meta cards in rank but if you just want to play casual you can and duel with friends too. I've spent many hours (mobile) on the game and rarely spent money for gems since the game gives you many way to get them.

review:
Considerando as poucas horas de gameplay que tive, n√£o sei se muitos ir√£o concordar com o que digo, por√©m √© justific√°vel. Come√ßando pelo meio de se obter decks, eu reclamaria pela quantidade de tempo gasto farmando que √© necess√°ria pra ter algo decente pra se jogar, n√£o, n√£o tem deck no jogo de f√°cil acesso que seja considerado decente pra jogar, vc pode comprar um estrutural de red eyes e pegar seu lend√°rio mas a dificuldade pra subir disso vai ser a de um parto, muitos podem me dizer "ah mas e normal farmar muito pra ficar forte num jogo, acontece, tem que investir horas", ok, entendo essa afirma√ß√£o, por√©m tenho dois pontos sobre isso:
- Primeiramente o farm √© muito mon√≥tono a ponto de voc√™ zerar um evento repetitivo e nada inovador super r√°pido e ficar repetindo duelos completamente entediantes e cansativos no port√£o do jogo, o farm n √© divertido como rpgs que vc sei la tenta fazer uma side-quest ou algo assim, o farm √© completamente envolto de repeti√ß√£o cansativa e obrigatoria pra conseguir ganhar recurso;
- Segundamente, n√£o necessariamente voc√™ farmando muito e conseguindo seu deck vai se dar bem em duelos de alto n√≠vel, pois cartas como "Compulsory Evacuation Devide", "Crackdown" e "ice dragon prison" s√£o cartas que ganham jogos somente com sua ativa√ß√£o (ice dragon prison tem esse fator de forma mais bruta) e as mesmas se encontram presas em caixas limitadas onde a op√ß√£o de compra por gema √© retirada a partir de certo n√∫mero de pacotes comprados, ou voc√™ tem sorte ou se voc√™ √© pobre voc√™ vai se fuder tomando uma dessa e n√£o tendo uma pra dar de volta.(Inclusive , o meta atual tem decks de for√ßa parecido, por√©m Phantom Knights tem essa vantagem sobres outros por poder usar essas famosas cartas da elite burguesa).
A empresa que gere o jogo √© t√£o problem√°tica ao ponto de inserir "macro" n√£o somente na m√£o inicial (onde eu por exemplo num deck de 30 cartas, comprei a √∫nica c√≥pia do dreadmaster que tenho no deck por fodendo cinco duelos seguidos) mas tamb√©m em caixas de cartas, muitos e muitos absurdos relatos s√£o postados de cartas UR de boxes que s√£o importantissimas ficarem pro pacote n√∫mero 1, eu jogo isso a cinco anos, j√° montei diversos decks usando dinheiro e principalmente gemas, e nenhum dos que tenho tive sorte de arranjar as cartas que eu queria no come√ßo, salvo minimas exce√ß√µes que consegui algo bom r√°pido que mesmo assim n impediram minha run pelo deck de ser longa e massante, meu deck de harpia fui at√© o fim da mini box 3 vezes, meu deck de pk fui at√© o fim da minobox 3 vezes, meu deck de hero me lembro at√© hoje, numa main box com 180 pacotes, minha primeira c√≥pia do Anki foi no pacote 17 e minha segunda no pacote 24,  meu red eyes meteor dragon venho por volta do pacote 20 e era a √∫nica que eu tinha um deck quase montado e interesse, tomei macro at√© mesmo em cartas R que estavam sendo muito usadas como por exemplo o megazord do super quantum, minha primeira c√≥pia dessa carta R s√≥ veio aparecer depois de comprar 110 pacotes numa main box, minha terceira c√≥pia do esmaecimento do vazio foi a R que mais demorou pra pegar e mesmo sendo R e tendo 6 copias na box eu s√≥ consegui depois de abrir a box duas vezes e na segunda vez peguei ela com 120 pacotes comprados.

Sim, eu tenho muitos relatos que ficaram marcados em mim pois eu tenho muito amor por esse jogo, por√©m o rumo que ele tomou com skills que jogam pelos players, selection box com cartas insanas e lockadas para os jogadores com menos dinheiro, com macro em m√£os iniciais e boxes e muitas outras coisas, reconhe√ßo que ningu√©m deve jogar isso e que s√≥ ser√° reformulado no momento que as pessoas pararem de jogar, por√©m sabemos que jogar de Yu-Gi-Oh! √© sequelado pelo jogo e infelizmente Duel Links √© uma das poucas op√ß√µes dispon√≠veis para os f√¢s do jogo e do anime.

Reconhe√ßo que o jogo consegue ser muito divertido, consegue render umas boas horas de entretenimento mas isso se deve pelo fato de Yu-Gi-Oh! ser um jogo de cartas muito dahora e contagiante, claro muitas √©pocas existiram e o jogo foi aumentando a complexidade mas √© divertido no geral e at√© faz a gente ignorar esses pormenores, por√©m esses ditos pormenores come√ßaram a me afetar ap√≥s muito tempo exposto a eles, entrem no jogo, joguem o jogo, mas saibam que em momentos voc√™s podem se frustrar por n√£o ter dinheiro e serem coagidos pelo pr√≥prio jogo gastar nos mesmos por querer um estrutural ou algo em selection, muitas vezes voc√™s v√£o perder um duelo porque o oponente apertou um bot√£o amarelo e deixou a skill fazer tudo sozinho, muitas vezes vcs v√£o querer uma carta e ela vai demorar muito pra vir, muitas vezes voc√™s v√£o receber blefes de brilhos UR abrindo pacotes pra na verdade ser uma carta N ou R, muitas vezes v√£o estar com sequencias de vit√≥rias e perder elas pelo servidor do jogo ser horr√≠vel, muitas vezes v√£o sacar a c√≥pia unica do seu deck na m√£o inicial de forma constante, muitas vezes v√£o jogar o mesmo evento de novo com mudan√ßas m√≠nimas , muitas vezes v√£o se ver horas farmando da mesma forma pra abrir 40 packs e as vezes nem isso, muitas vezes o jogo vai te dar gemas de recompensa e voc√™ vai gastar elas e n pegar nada e acabar percebendo que 1000 gemas s√£o 20 pacotes duma main box com 180 pacotes que voc√™ abre 3 vezes.

author: {'steamid': '76561199446451949', 'num_games_owned': 271, 'num_reviews': 3, 'playtime_forever': 524, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 468, 'last_played': 1688646110}
review:
A surprisingly fair monetization model for a F2P game published by Konami, no premium currency, and all in-game currencies are earned solely through gameplay, you can however spend real money to buy structure decks or packs but all in-game currencies can be earned in abundance through leveling up characters, pvp, missions, and events. There's usually a main event every week along with a side event or two, prizes for which often include plenty of cards, gems, cosmetic card sleeves, and game mats as well as a new character every so often. There is plenty of deck build possibilities providing varied and deep gameplay, typically exemplified by card archetypes, of which there are plenty.

I do however wish there were more permanent and involved single-player content, more duel formats that remain available outside of events, and the starter decks for almost every character are practically unusable, which can severely hinder the early game experience and is only slightly offset by the admittedly sizable amount of free giveaways that new and returning players are often hit with.

author: {'steamid': '76561199095501152', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 2, 'playtime_forever': 8951, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 8951, 'last_played': 1652776328}
review:
Duel Links es un juegazo en el tema artistico. 10/10. Incluso mejor que algunos juegos de Yu-Gi-Oh

Recomendaba mucho este juego. Pero ya no m√°s. Konami ha estado destruyendo este juego poco a poco. Literalmente ahora ya no puedes hacer un deck competitivo.

¬øPor que?
Simple. Demoras en farmear gemas como loco, te mamas HORAS Y HORAS en completar la mayoria de eventos QUE SON ABURRIDOS A MAS NO PODER. Consigues despu√©s de semanas todas las cartas que estan repartidas en MUCHAS cajas. y cuando por fin tienes tu deck competitivo, te cae banlist o aparece un deck mejor al siguiente mes. Que deja inutil a tu deck competitivo.
Puedes hacer nuevamente la tarea de los eventos y tener MUCHISIMA MAS PACIENCIA DE LA QUE YA TENIAS. Pero no, cada vez se hace mas imposible. 
Konami ahora deja una miseria de gemas. Con ese deck competitivo que farmeaste a lo mucho podr√°s llegar a Platino, o si tienes mucha suerte, a Leyenda. Y lo peor es que cada vez este modelo de farmeo se vuelve tedioso, y en un todo, terminar√°s odiando el juego. 

Y ahi es cuando entra el P2W. Seamos honestos. este juego es P2W. No P2F. Actualmente es imposible tener los deck meta a tiempo, y cuando los tienes, o te cae baneo, o ya ha aparecido un deck mas competente que el demoraste semanas en obtener. Esto me ha pasado muchas veces. Juego esto con mi movil desde el 2018 hasta el 2022 porque se hizo horrible. 

En conclusion. Si quieres jugar Duel Links, solo juega casual. Si quieres jugar competitivo, mejor compra las cartas fisicas. Creeme que ser√° una mejor inversi√≥n.

author: {'steamid': '76561198822832105', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 37, 'playtime_forever': 180, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 180, 'last_played': 1593971432}
review:
Had probably 400+ hours on mobile, maybe more, between enjoying world chat (before spam bot garbage) and casual/ranked play.

It was good back when it released and for the first three years. Started to simply be watered down modern YGO after adding link summons.

It's a shame because, while all this isn't a bad thing for more modern competitive/contemporary players, this game captured (or rather "had") the charm of that old school style YGO (later adding GX, 5D's, etc). 

After they added Syncro, it was clear to me what would eventually follow. So I just enjoyed the game for what it was while I could. And that truly was nice while it lasted. I appreciate how the earlier versions of DL brought in both new players and old school players like myself to this clear labor of love.

Nowadays, unless the speed duel format is your preferred cup of coffee, you might as well just go play Master Duel now. GGs.

review: If you are wanting to go into PVP, you better prepare a Tier 0 deck and your ass (the latter in case it gets beaten by a player who can be an asshole and wreck your strategy come Turn 2). Because of the way PVP events and PVP duels are set up in Duel Links, you will lose almost 100% of the time, it's too unfair for casual players like me who just want to have fun (But then again, how can you have fun when your main objective is to win against everyone you come across? But instead of winning against everyone, I'm blocking everyone. Just to make sure they don't face off with me again). I'm so sick of this bullshit, I'm taking a hiatus the moment a new PVP event starts up. KC Cup, World Riding Duel Grand Prix, Action Duel PVP event, etc. All these events can go kiss my ass. The only thing I want from this game going forward is LESS PVP, MORE PVE!!! SCREW PVP, shove it up your ass!

review: Let me start out by saying I'm a huge Yu-Gi-Oh! fan, but I'm a bigger Kaiba fan myself. In short, I went with the full on Blue Eyes White Dragon deck, pimped that bad boy out with some Alternate Blue Eyes White Dragon, Sage with the Blue Eyes and some other cards of the names I can't recall. My deck was killer!! I floored some punks around town like it was nothing. And then they started link summoning and I lost on turn 1 when I couldn't even summon anything. That's when I realised, I'm trash at this game and will probably never be good again. So I pushed for all the achievements and called it a day.

review: The classic Yu-gi-oh card game in a quick-play, 3 card format. The desire to get certain cards for my deck kept me playing and coming back. It is difficult to get the cards you need if you don't plan on buying with real money. Despite that, the desire to win and the desire to improve your deck will most likely keep you hooked, especially if you have some nostalgia for the anime.

Al√©m disso, trazem diversos personagens hist√≥ricos da franquia, independente de qual gera√ß√£o seja, sem falar nos diferentes ambientes de jogo e personaliza√ß√£o que oferece. The auto-setting to refresh boxes after you collected all UR's is malicious af bc the cards I wanted are SR's and pull chances are already garbage when you can pull 20+ copies of the worthless filth commons. Master Duel is superior in every way except AI RNG, they're both busted with cheating to provide 'challenge.' Just simply not worth grinding my life away to get anywhere in this game, and with expirations on freebies just solidify my motivation to never come back to this atrocious game.

review:
+ Speed Duel format is more simple and easier to follow.
+ The card pool is (used to be) tailored to prevent certain crazy things that used to occur in the TCG.
+ Certain decks that never flourished IRL got their big time in this game.
+ The character and anime integrations are a very nice touch. Very expressive and entertaining.

- Time-gated unlocks behind events.
- Very grindy, time consuming, and much less f2p. If you want a super meta deck NOW before people start expecting it to be hit on the banlist expect to pay $$$.
- Box model is very meh. Older archetypes and generic staple cards can be in older boxes containing mostly non-relevant cards, but this is usually what dream tickets are for.
- Lately the devs have been very liberal with their skill/balance design and card releases (game-defining staple cards exclusive to newer limited-time BOXes, full power mekk knights, almost all of gouki, xyz galaxy skill) which has led to pretty toxic formats. Powercreep moment, the worst part is that IT CAN GET WORSE.

As a f2p player who has gotten dlv20 many times, I'd say the game is fine to play as long as you don't spend egregious amounts of money. It's still possible to build good decks as long as you save gems and be responsible about what BOXes you open and when.

review: It is Yu-Gi-Oh but Speed Duel format. It was seen as better before Master Duel came around, which has a better monetization scheme but Duel Links has a lot better single player content and not just "do a section of campaigns for decks that were only meta a decade ago at best" and then do the Ranked Latter. If you want to play Speed Duel Format instead of Master Duel format though, this game is for you! If you don't... Play Master Duel or a fan simulator! Master Duel used to not be an option but it is now! And the card pool is very similar due to the updates Duel Links has been getting!

author: {'steamid': '76561198338825890', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 3, 'playtime_forever': 4637, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 4637, 'last_played': 1632559555}
review: Game used to be very fun for having all of the best parts of Yugioh but with the curated card list that omitted most (unfortunately not all) of the egregious design mistakes made in paper. As years went on and power creep took its course, it lost that charm, and now it's just become baby IRL yugioh, in which case just play it in paper. I genuinely uninstalled the moment they added Link Summoning, because that was by far the worst mechanic added to the actual game, somehow trumping Pendulums. I've played Yugioh competitively for many, many years and I understand it very well. I think what Duel Links attempted to do was worthy of merit, but alas all good things must end. I'm sure it has appeal somewhere in its current design, it just doesn't do what I wanted out of it anymore. Also, after playing Master Duel the lack of ability to dismantle garbage towards making cards you actually want feels fucking atrocious.

review:
What keeps me playing: 
- Fully voiced, dynamic avatars from across all the series. 
- Surprising amount of voice lines covering multitude of cards, summons, activation, etc. 
- Avatar Skills! It is honestly a refreshing thing to see, and I love being able to pull out a 7 Completed from Bandit Keith's sleeve. 
- Plentiful PvE casual duels, challenging PvE events and bosses and I never feel pressured to play PvP. 

I always find myself coming back to this one over Link Evolution or Master Duel. The gem grind can be a little bit of a pain but doesn't feel as bad as other games.

author: {'steamid': '76561198047278476', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 48, 'playtime_forever': 4293, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 815, 'last_played': 1710610023}
review:
Duel Links is Yu-Gi-Oh Lite. A more restricted, faster paced game with a focus on the anime and its characters. You build your deck, select your favorite character from whichever series, and then duel to earn access to more cards and abilities. Each character has a set of abilities that can be used in duels if certain conditions are met, adding a layer of strategy.

 I primarily play on mobile, and as far as mobile games go, I find it to be more consumer friendly than most.

author: {'steamid': '76561198056711152', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 1, 'playtime_forever': 26683, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 509, 'playtime_at_review': 24649, 'last_played': 1712073615}
review:
As of review post. 410 hours played on Yu-Gi-Oh Duel Links (Perfected Achievements):

Likes
- The art style, it's very anime with some cool looking animations for very recognisable monsters
- Different rules to regular Yu-gi-oh, not as complicated generally. (Expanded overtime)
- Quick and easy to also play on the go (Mobile friendly)
- It can be very fun to watch online, i.e. Replays from tournaments/deck profiles/farm decks etc.
- Filter and sort options are excellent compared to other style games, there's search/popular cards/decklists.
- Trying to add your own challenges can make the game more fun, i.e. you can copy opponents decks/lists
- Skills for the characters gives more variety, it's unique in that respect generally.
- There's a ton of ways to play now, you can focus on say a particular deck you like or just play casual.

Dislike
- Sometimes when you login there's a ton of pop up type actions to perform can get annoying after a while.
- There's not really any incentives for extra gold once you have most things unlocked (This may Change?)
- Some of the older events were really good but have never really came back unfortunately.
- There's a lot of newer cards from recent years still missing meaning some decks are quite underpowered.
- "Some skills and characters are quite difficult to unlock" unless you really go out of your way to get them.
- Many of the previous better skills got massive restrictions so now nearly useless to the average player.

Why I would recommend:
- It's Free (Plenty of stuff is given out quite regularly)
- Pretty simple to understand and play if you have ever played any standard Yu-gi-oh at all
- It's a very mobile friendly game so can play on the go when out and about
- Has quite regular updates ie. new events/card boxes/bug fixes/limit list/characters etc.
- Fun to play with a friend/small group, especially if you set up your "own rules".
- There's not really a limit/end game, because there's new regular content and the "meta" changes often.

*Note this is coming as a free to play player who has been playing since the game was released.

EDIT (on 24/01/24) : 
Rush Duels being added since my first review has given the game a new way to play it.
- There's a new ranked ladder option with new characters to level up, rush duel boxes/structures
- Gems you do earn from it can also be used in the main speed duel parts of duel links which makes it an extra source of easy gems even if you don't want to play it much. 

All in all it's a nice addition to an already amazing versatile game for yugioh fans alike, I wouldn't be surprised if we see more and more new rush duel characters/cards over the next few years further increasing the games already great potential.

author: {'steamid': '76561199073604270', 'num_games_owned': 288, 'num_reviews': 41, 'playtime_forever': 1906, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 1906, 'last_played': 1678187286}
review:
If you're looking for a review on this game you've come to the wrong place, but if you're looking for an outstanding pie recipe you've come to the right place.

Ingredients:

1. 6 tablespoons unsalted butter
2. 1/2 cup white sugar
3. 1/2 cup brown sugar
4. 1/4 cup water
5. 1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
6. 1 pinch salt
7. 5 apples - peeled, cored and sliced
8. 1 pastry for double-crust pie

Directions:

1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees F (220 degrees C).
2. Combine butter, white sugar, brown sugar, water, cinnamon, and salt in a saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and set aside.
3. Roll out half the pastry to fit a 9-inch pie plate. Place bottom crust in pie plate; pour in apple slices.
4. Roll out top crust into a 10-inch circle. Cut into 8 (1-inch) wide strips with a sharp paring knife or pastry wheel. Weave the pastry strips, one at a time, into a lattice pattern. Fold the ends of the lattice strips under the edge of the bottom crust and crimp to seal.
5. Pour butter-sugar mixture over top of pie, coating the lattice, and allowing any remaining sauce to drizzle through the crust.
6. Bake in the preheated oven for 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C), and bake until the crust is golden brown, the caramel on the top crust is set, and the apple filling is bubbling, 35 to 40 more minutes. Allow to cool completely before slicing.

review:
I don't play a lot of deck-builder games, Duel Links has been the best. And though the updates and events may be slow sometimes, you can actually do well as a Free to Play player, unlike a lot of the others. I highly recommend duel links.

My only feedback really is that Pendulum Zones should not be locked to certain characters, and it should be universally available. The way they have it now, unless you have certain skills, your Pendulum zones take up your Spell/Trap card zones, which is not good.

review: I have been playing Yu-Gi-Oh! since the late 2000s and i have pretty much seen the entire scene develop. When it comes to this game i have also been playing it since day 1 with a couple of breaks here and there. But i can safely say that i think its finally time for me to put this game to rest, it was a fun experience but i would not recommend this game in 2023 to anyone. If you still want to play a Yu-Gi-Oh! game master duel is better because of the variety of decks. its cheaper to build any deck(s) you want but there is still a fuck tonne of grind. I would not recommend any of these games but if you absolutely want to play something Master Duel is an objectively better Yu-Gi-Oh! experience.

review: PvE is great, being able to use jank against ai is endlessly fun. Events are plentiful and mostly fun, always something going on. PvP is fun and fast paced, but this is where you'll find the gap between new players and old players is the biggest, strictly card-pool speaking. Pulling cards is a pain, honestly. The feeling of pulling a card you want loses its luster after you've opened 178/180 packs of the box for it. Aside from the annoying way we can obtain cards, this game is great and supremely addicting.

review: Overall, Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links is a fun and engaging mobile game for fans of the franchise. The graphics are great, the gameplay is smooth and easy to pick up, and the card pool is vast. However, the game does have its downsides, particularly its pay-to-win system and matchmaking, which can make it difficult to progress without spending real money. Additionally, there are also a number of bugs and glitches that can be frustrating. While fans of the series may enjoy the game despite its issues, others may want to look for alternative card games.

review: I am extremely disappointed with this Yu Gi Oh game. The fact that there are characters of different races included is completely unacceptable. How dare they try to include diversity in a children's card game? It's clear that the creators are just trying to be politically correct and it ruins the entire experience for me. I will never purchase another Yu Gi Oh product again. Keep your diversity out of my childhood memories.

author: {'steamid': '76561198067891387', 'num_games_owned': 39, 'num_reviews': 2, 'playtime_forever': 60665, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 40597, 'last_played': 1709067793}
review:
Pretty much same as anyone else says on here, this game has maybe 2 or 3 decks that are just better than any other deck that can be made. 

The game basically gets boring AF because in order to succeed without paying there is maybe 1 deck you will be able to (partially) make and then you can only play that boring drag over and over again, still losing to every person you come across that has dropped loads of money into the game to get full play-sets of UR and SR cards that to get one copy of with only gems would take buying anywhere from 20 to 60 packs. (good ol' scum of the earth dropping their not-so-hard earned cash on games, ruining the game for those of us who work hard for the salary we earn with those quarter a year hourly wage raise which totally keeps us from drowning in debt...)

It is also constantly disappointing because there are tons of different interesting engines that just aren't worthy of using, partially again because slimy, wealthy, albeit probably depressed and lonely, turd eaters, who spend money on this game, but also partially because Konami is either to unintelligent to create parody, or too soulless. (my bet honestly is on both)

Don't get me wrong, I obviously play this game plenty, I make Platinum every refresh of the PVP (which probably isn't that impressive, but once you get to platinum it becomes relatively pointless to even apply oneself to further heights), but honestly if you have any way of playing Yu-Gi-Oh with friends or on a home-brew game or even a classic game (gameboy advance, ps2, etc.) Those are gonna be your best bet for entertainment that doesn't make you want to just swear off this game alltogether.

author: {'steamid': '76561198132273302', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 20, 'playtime_forever': 1636, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 1636, 'last_played': 1672002191}
review:
I like the speed duel format in concept, but what an ugly, annoying game that Konami has wrapped it up in. 

Every time you enter the game, you're forced to endure multiple long forced promotion screens popping up. Then, if there's an event, you're forced to suffer through one of their shottily animated, slow cutscenes. When you do get into the game, you have to navigate between menus through their ugly, clunky street-view interface. And beyond that, you need to toggle between yugioh generations to reach certain screens. It is very poorly done. 

There are far too many currencies / collectables, to the point that it's overwhelming for new players as well as returning players. The key/portal system is grindy and not fun. Grinding against CPU players on the streets is slow and boring. It's too bad that they feature singleplayer vs AI so prominently in this game only to make it so unenjoyable. 

On the bright side, they went on to do a much better job with the interfaces in Master Duel. Less is more. Hopefully, they bring the Rush duel format over to america eventually and do a better job with the game.

They only thing I would want to alter is make some of the rarer cards to be a little easier to obtain but even still there is an amazing card selection and even if you don't get the specific card you want you get plenty of cards to choose from to take it's place and can even stride to fill in the cards you don't have after auto building a deck and seeing what you are missing, using that can give you an idea of what some good decks can be and even test them out to see how they work and how they would fair against other duelist who are real people.

author: {'steamid': '76561198087957579', 'num_games_owned': 583, 'num_reviews': 24, 'playtime_forever': 842, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 1, 'playtime_at_review': 434, 'last_played': 1712288123}
review:
My initial impressions of this game were not positive. The starter decks are god awful and I got trounced even in the lowest ranks of bronze PvP. Coming into this game, I new nothing of how to play Yugioh (although I have experience in other card games, like Hearthstone) and I was pretty intimidated by the long chains people were pulling off with their cards. I was about ready to give up when I happened to pull an Ancient Gear solider from a card pack. Ancient Gear Soldier happens to be a god awful card, but I remember it being one of my favorites as a kid since I loved the aesthetic (I collected the cards but never played the game). This inspired me to see if there were any Ancient Gear oriented decks, and sure enough their is! I admittedly had to drop a little bit of Christmas money into packs (thankfully not much), but I got enough cards to construct a meta Ancient Gear deck. After that, I fell in love with the game. As someone who had no experience with this game, it took some reading and experimenting the last day to figure things out. However, now that I have I am really enjoying this game. I will also say that it helped my enjoyment that Ancient Gear happened to also be the exact archetype I would want to play in a card game. I am a big fan of summoning large monsters to overwhelm my opponent and the deck does exactly that! That turned out to be quite a fortunate coincidence.

TL:DR, A bit difficult (and potentially frustrating) to initially get into, especially if you are unfamiliar with how Yugioh plays. However, it can be a lot of fun if you put some time into understanding the game mechanics and find your niche.

review: Fun game to play, despite the release of master duel it still holds up well as it has many gameplay features that makes it unique compared to master duel. Skills are a great addition to duel links as it allows for greater deck building possibilities and fun matches. Also unlike master duel I don't have the time to go make myself an entire sandwich, clean the house and make some tea during my opponent's turn as duel links is more fast paced. Overall I think its a good game even though it could sometimes feel a bit grindy to get the cards you want if you are a F2P player.

author: {'steamid': '76561198289200795', 'num_games_owned': 1177, 'num_reviews': 241, 'playtime_forever': 1433, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 1433, 'last_played': 1622451773}
review:
It's Yugioh, but faster and with skills.

Honestly I prefer regular Yugioh matches, rather than these quick matches which have their own meta because of the skills system, but it was still fun to play before Master Duel came out.

I personally think that Yugioh already is really difficult because making a 'meta' or even competitively viable deck is really difficult because there are so many cards, and adding skills just makes this that much more difficult. This is probably because I am just not that good at Yugioh, but I still think that the skills just make it too difficult.

Also I do not like the temporary events and time limits on being able to redeem your free card vouchers.

I would still recommend this game if you like Yugioh but I personally prefer Master Duel.

You are a company of cash grabbing apes that need to be stopped.  When I think about opening this game I feel bad for how many people you have bankrupted from their gambling addictions.  This is worse than CSGO lotto and Fortnite skins combined.  I don't even know why I bother why I write this review because with each key I press I know that you are making more money from your whales that want your $19 fortinite gift cards.  You have ruined this game beyond repair.  Your garbage cut scenes say more than what I can describe in words for how cringe it is.  I can't skip the abhorrent cut scenes no matter how hard I click my mouse.  This cursed game is a disgrace to human kind and deserves to be thrown into a lake of fire.

With utmost hatred and disregard,
I hope this game dies immediately.

 In the meantime you are happy you got to summon a plain text Dark Magician.

author: {'steamid': '76561199134836045', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 12, 'playtime_forever': 23442, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 14551, 'last_played': 1698605086}
review: I loved the Yu-Gi-Oh! anime growing up and Duel Links was made with that audience in mind. It has a large and ever-expanding cast of playable and unlock-able characters from each different series of the anime. From the OG Duel Monsters series with Yugi & Kaiba, right up until the V-RAINS series as of the recent Link summoning update. All of these characters are voiced by their respective voice actors from the shows too and that's a massive plus. Mix that with a faster-paced and more casual approach to the Yu-Gi-Oh! card game and Duel Links is easily my favourite free-to-play game that I've played, as well as a top 5 entry for Yu-Gi-Oh! video games.

author: {'steamid': '76561198164670585', 'num_games_owned': 552, 'num_reviews': 24, 'playtime_forever': 1578, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 1578, 'last_played': 1601892466}
review:
Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links is a collectible card game that has gained a significant following among fans of the original Yu-Gi-Oh! anime and manga series. The game, which is available on iOS and Android devices, allows players to create and customize their own decks featuring their favorite characters and monsters from the series and duel against other players online.

Overall, I really enjoyed my time with Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links. The gameplay is smooth and intuitive, with a tutorial mode that does a great job of introducing new players to the mechanics of the game. The sound effects and music are well done, with the iconic theme songs from the anime series adding an extra layer of nostalgia for fans of the show. The graphics are also fairly good for a mobile game, with the character and monster designs looking faithful to their counterparts in the anime.

One aspect of the game that I particularly appreciated was the variety of modes available to play. In addition to the standard ranked and unranked duels, there are also special events featuring unique challenges and rewards, as well as a story mode that allows players to relive classic moments from the anime series. This helps to keep the game feeling fresh and gives players a reason to come back and play more.

While the game is certainly enjoyable, there are a few areas that could be improved upon. One issue I had was with the in-game purchases, which can give players an advantage over their opponents by allowing them to buy new cards or packs. While it's not necessary to spend real money to be successful in the game, it can certainly give players an edge and may turn off those who don't want to spend extra money on a mobile game. Additionally, the load times for certain modes and events can be a bit slow at times, which can be frustrating when trying to jump into a quick match.

Comparing Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links to other collectible card games, I would say that it holds up well. The gameplay is solid and the inclusion of characters and monsters from the anime series adds an extra layer of depth for fans of the show. While the in-game purchases and slow load times can be a bit of a drawback, they don't detract too much from the overall experience. Overall, I would give Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Links a 8 out of 10. It's a fun and engaging game that's sure to appeal to fans of the series and collectible card games in general.

review:
Honestly, I want to love this game. YGO was the biggest card game for me growing up. There's a lot of good things about this online version, but there's a lot more negatives than positives. The format isn't horrible, but the staples and packs are very poorly distributed. Furthermore, the insane amount of ingame popups really eats away at my soul when booting up the game, and there's no way to disable them permanently (only day-to-day).

I wish they had streamline more of the UI, because the music, the special effects, art style are quite nice. It's the clunky nature of the overall game that drags down the experience.

author: {'steamid': '76561198093847850', 'num_games_owned': 743, 'num_reviews': 27, 'playtime_forever': 21344, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 16496, 'last_played': 1685568497}
review:
I'd like to ease into this review by giving a little context. I am a long-time Yu-Gi-Oh fan, I loved it as a kid almost twenty years ago and, to some degree, I continue to love it to this day. Things have changed since then, like a childhood friend you haven't seen since you moved away from your hometown, but nevertheless the game still has some of it's charm. You can continue to play most of the decks and play most of the cards you used to, if you're like me, but they're overall success is dependent on the meta.

The Yu-Gi-Oh meta has greatly changed since then but this review isn't about the meta, or the TCG per se, instead this review is about Duel Links specifically.

Duel links, unlike similar TCGs such as Hearthstone, is extremely accommodating to newer players giving them ample opportunity to buy card packs through a method other than in-game purchases, although they are available to you, as well as auto-deck building tools, pre-made deck sets and more.

Sure there are other places you could be playing Yu-Gi-Oh but, in my personal opinion, this is a good place to start and a greater place to stay.

review: Eu sou um pai de 45 anos, provavelmente uma das pessoas mais velhas a jogar este jogo. Sou pai solteiro criando meu filho, que agora tem 14 anos. Meu filho ganhou este jogo no Natal de 2021 de seu tio, ent√£o o instalamos em seu computador e ele come√ßou a jogar. At√© o final da semana ele tinha 24 horas neste jogo. Isso foi horr√≠vel para mim, pois j√° era dif√≠cil encontrar maneiras de passar o tempo com meu filho, pois ele est√° sempre com os amigos ou apenas assistindo ao YouTube. Ent√£o eu decidi fazer uma conta no Steam e pegar esse jogo para ver se eu poderia jogar ao lado dele. author: {'steamid': '76561198044682260', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 19, 'playtime_forever': 5675, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 1766, 'last_played': 1681445380}
review:
I've played Magic, Digimon, WIXOSS, Pokemon, Hearthstone, Keyforge, Transformers, Force of Will.

So I think I have a good understanding of trading card games.

For a long time I was put off by Yugioh from it's art work, but diving deeper into it while I do find many cards subjectively ugly there's some really good art as well especially with newer cards.

From a game perspective, it's solid. The app is on PC and mobile. Fairly stable, sometimes brief "retry connection" errors. The animations, sound effects and voice lines are high quality.

The economy is quite fair giving you premium currency from just playing to buy booster packs, decks, cosmetics. (I would say the economy is vastly more fair than Magic Arenas)

Game play is varied but the meta is win turn 2 or you lose. Which Yugioh is infamous for, and it's kind of annoying. You can add a bunch of counter play traps and spells to your deck but then that ruins your win condition.

>Turn 2: play half your deck to special summon 10 monsters to get 1-3 huge monsters out to one turn K.O.

Going first feels like you auto lose because you can't attack on turn 1. It's a problem but that is Yugioh. 

I'm still a new player, the learning curve is kind of rough but there is a good game here, especially for free.

review:
Desde o lan√ßamento de Yu-Gi-Oh, diversos foram os jogos que tentaram emular o jogo de cartas em ambientes virtuais. Afirmo sem a menor d√∫vida, Duel Links foi o primeiro grande sucesso. 
Apesar de possuir regras distintas do jogo tradicional, as adapta√ß√µes feitas casaram muito bem com o jogo. 
A disponibilidade de cartas que o jogo possui √© imensa, praticamente todas existentes. 
Al√©m disso, trazem diversos personagens hist√≥ricos da franquia, independente de qual gera√ß√£o seja, sem falar nos diferentes ambientes de jogo e personaliza√ß√£o que oferece. 
Resumindo: boa interface e boa imers√£o no universo Yu-Gi-Oh. O jogo possui uma grande quantidade de eventos (alguns repetitivos), mas oferece diversas formas de jogo. 
O modo PvP √© bom, mas complicado, bem dif√≠cil na verdade; pois quem n√£o coloca dinheiro no jogo fica dependente de determinados decks para subir, e se algum desses decks perderem for√ßa, fica dif√≠cil encontrar outros. 
No geral, √© um bom jogo. A experi√™ncia de jogo √© √≥tima, e na data de lan√ßamento foi realmente algo inovador. A parte ruim √© que √© dif√≠cil manter uma regularidade no jogo, e da trabalho conseguir as cartas. Por√©m para quem gosta de Yu-Gi-Oh, √© uma boa pedida.

review:
Pros:
- Can grind character EXP for gems.
- Always have events running.
- Simpler and shorter than the standard format (could be a cons for some).
- Cards in the boxes are guaranteed as long as you keep digging. Still expensive though.

Cons:
- Can't craft cards like in Master Duel.
- Cheat character skills that can change/nerf for the publisher to drive sales to new box.
- Outdated cards. So many cards still not released.
- Selection boxes are paywalled, although they can be gotten from dream tickets.

author: {'steamid': '76561197991585188', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 15, 'playtime_forever': 171215, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 756, 'playtime_at_review': 124469, 'last_played': 1712372713}
review:
Some people think that this game is obsolete since Master Duel is released.
But Master Duel cannot replace Duel Links in many ways. Duel Links has many things that makes it much better for many players. Some of them that come into my mind:
1. Actual anime characters with their personalities
2. Voice lines during battle
3. Special 3D animations for summons of iconic monsters
4. PvE. A lot of PvE for those who doesn't like PvP that much.
5. Interesting events with storyline, dialogues, jokes etc.
6. Unique rewards for events, be it cards or skills. I like the feeling of getting something special for participating in the event, not only gems.
7. Skills. This makes deckbuilding and the game itself incredibly different from a regular game without skills. Also this allows building decks that are not possible to make in a game without skills.
8. Length of the game. In no way I can spend 30+ minues on 1 duel. Sometimes I have to wait over 5 minutes while my opponents makes a turn in Master Duel.
9. Consistency of the decks. Since there are only 20 cards in the deck, and still 3 copies of a card - I can see the cards I want more often.
10. New beta mode called Legacy duels. Finally there is a way to play oldschool battles without all new summon mechanics.
11. Excitement while opening booster boxes. The excitement I feel while spending my hard-earned gems on a box is comparable to the one I feel in real life while opening packs. When I open the single I want from the first 10 packs out of 200 - that's insane amount of emotions Master Duels in uncapable of providing. Crafting any card you want is convenient and fast, but dull and emotionless.
